06048nam a22009255i 9780271063003DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710630037 a10.1515/97802710630032doi  a(DE-B1597)584213  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE49.2.G3bP43 2013 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a973/.043102aA Peculiar Mixture :bGerman-Language Cultures and Identities in Eighteenth-Century North America /ced. by Jan Stievermann, Oliver Scheiding. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b20 illustrations/2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMax Kade Research Institute: Germans Beyond Europe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 Migration and Settlement -- t1 Rethinking the Significance of the 1709 Mass Migration -- t2 Information Brokers and Mediators -- t3 The Palatine Immigrants of 1710 and the Native Americans -- tPart 2 Material and Intellectual Cultures in the Making -- t4 Of Dwelling Houses, Painted Chests, and Stove Plates -- t5 (Re)Discovering the German-Language Literature of Colonial America -- t6 "Runs, Creeks, and Rivers Join" -- t7 Divergent Paths -- t8 Defining the Limits of American Liberty -- t9 Pennsylvania German Taufscheine and Revolutionary America -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough innovative interdisciplinary methodologies and fresh avenues of inquiry, the nine essays collected in A Peculiar Mixture endeavor to transform how we understand the bewildering multiplicity and complexity that characterized the experience of German-speaking people in the middle colonies. They explore how the various cultural expressions of German speakers helped them bridge regional, religious, and denominational divides and eventually find a way to partake in America's emerging national identity. Instead of thinking about early American culture and literature as evolving continuously as a singular entity, the contributions to this volume conceive of it as an ever-shifting and tangled "web of contact zones." They present a society with a plurality of different native and colonial cultures interacting not only with one another but also with cultures and traditions from outside the colonies, in a "peculiar mixture" of Old World practices and New World influences. Aside from the editors, the contributors are Rosalind J. Beiler, Patrick M. Erben, Cynthia G. Falk, Marie Basile McDaniel, Philip Otterness, Liam Riordan, Matthias Schönhofer, and Marianne S. Wokeck.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aGerman AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aGerman AmericansxHistoryx18th century. 0aGerman AmericansxHistoryy18th century. 0aGerman Americans. 0aGermansxEthnic identityxNorth America. 0aGermansxEthnic identity. 0aGermansxHistoryx18th centuryxNorth America. 0aGermanszNorth AmericaxEthnic identity. 0aGermanszNorth AmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aGermans. 0aGermanyxEmigration and immigrationxHistoryx18th century. 0aHISTORYxColonial Period (1600-1775)xUnited States. 0aHISTORYxState & LocalxGeneralxUnited States. 0aNorth AmericaxEmigration and immigrationxHistoryx18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aBeiler, Rosalind J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErben, Patrick M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Cynthia G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDaniel, Marie Basile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtt